<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Comments on Deadline </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1403121994 Tallinn BNS in English 1335 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1403121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Mar 12, BNS -- Russia has made no promises to 
Estonia and Latvia about withdrawing its troops from those 
countries by Aug. 31, 1994, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister 
Vitaliy Churkin said in an interview with the Latvia-based Diena 
newspaper. 
  The Russian diplomat admitted, however, that Moscow has not 
officially refused to pull out its troops. 
  Churkin said the Russian Foreign Ministry has adopted a new 
tactical line, that of ignoring Baltic diplomats' critical 
statements. "At the recent sessions of the Council of Europe 
Security Council and the North Atlantic Cooperation Council 
(Russian Foreign Minister Andrey) Kozyrev didn't say a word 
about his Baltic colleagues, although we don't see eye to eye 
with them on a number of issues, including observance of human 
rights," he said. 
  Churkin assured that, as an official in charge of relations 
with the Baltic states at the Russian Foreign Ministry, he has 
"no evil intentions" with regard to those countries, and 
promised to do his best in seeking concrete solutions to the 
problems that have cropped up. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

