<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: 81 Percent Face `Serious' Hardships </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1403210194 Tallinn BNS in English 1820 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1403210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Mar 14, BNS -- Around 52.2 percent of Latvian 
families find it difficult to make both ends meet at the end of 
month, according to a public opinion poll, conducted by the 
State Statistics Committee. 
  The poll showed that 13.9 percent of families live on 
earlier 
savings, 14.9 percent have enough money but 0.7 percent are 
amply provided. 
  In total, 81 percent of families face serious money 
hardships. 
  Sixty-eight percent of respondents reported unable to save 
in 
the present conditions. Almost two-thirds of the interviewed 
said they could not make valuable purchases and would not be 
able to do it in the next twelve months, either. 
  The economic standing of families became worse between 1992 
and 1993, say the majority of respondents. Only 0.6 percent of 
families said they enjoyed an improvement in their material 
situation last year. 
  In addition, the families criticize the changes in the 
Latvian economic situation in 1993. Sixty-one percent of 
families say the economic situation became worse during the past 
year while 7.5 percent say the economic situation improved. 
  The poll interviewed 1,298 families. From those, 56 percent 
were urban dwellers and 46 percent lived in the countryside. 
The poll was aimed at studying the public opinion on the latest 
material welfare and economic situation changes in families. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

