<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Statistics Committee on Population Exodus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1403120294 Tallinn BNS in English 1335 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1403120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Mar 12, BNS -- Latvia's population decreased 
28,000 in 1993 on the account of interstate migration, according 
to figures from the State Statistics Committee. 
  As many as 19,291 person resettled for permanent residence 
in 
Russia, 5,120 left for Belarus, 3,427 for Ukraine and for Israel. 
  The population exodus to neighboring Lithuania and Estonia 
was 346 and 99, respectively. Another 744 people went to live 
in Germany, 559 in the United States, 34 in Canada and 32 to 
Australia. 
  Ethnically speaking, emigrants included 17,762 Russians, 
3,681 Belarusians, 3,676 Ukrainians, 1,161 Hebrews, 448 Poles, 
236 Germans and 205 Lithuanians. 
  As a result of migration processes, the number of ethnic 
Latvians among permanent residents increased 382 people last 
year. 

</TEXT>

