<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Maritime Kray, Japan Combat Radioactive Waste </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503100394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0717 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Leonid Vinogradov] </F>
  [Text] Vladivostok March 15 TASS -- Russia's Maritime 
Territory and Japan are pooling efforts to combat their common 
trouble -- the pollution of the Sea of Japan with the 
radioactive waste. The territorial administration head, 
Yevgeniy Nazdratenko, said specialists of the neighbouring 
country will install two waste-processing facilities to treat 
water used in nuclear submarine reactor. 
  Equipment of this kind has long been used in Japan and has 
proved a reliable tool in reducing radioactivity in waste to 
required level. 
  The first technological line will be installed in the Zvezda 
factory which repairs nuclear submarines in the city Bolshoy 
Kamen. Another installation will be attached to the Pacific 
Fleet. Russia's Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev, who visited 
Vladivostok on Monday, promised assistance in handling the 
project. 

</TEXT>

