<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pensioners Protest Inadequate Pensions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503114794 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503114794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in 
Estonian at 1000 GMT on 15 March broadcasts a 5.-minute report 
on a meeting of pensioners in Tallinn today, near the parliament 
and government building on Toompea Square. The unidentified 
correspondent notes that Marju Lauristin, the minister of social 
affairs, was surrounded by pensioners eager to voice their 
grievances and she promised to convey their problems to the 
government, which is scheduled to meet this morning. 
  The correspondent then interviews Lauristin who says that 
the 
pensions issue is a priority for the government but extra money 
is hard to find. "What we have done now," she explains, "is to 
provide compensation totalling 200 million kroons for domestic 
bills and there is a law on increasing pensions being debated 
now -- another 200 millions are needed for that. To the 
population at large this will seem like a crumb to a beggar. 
And public discontent is particularly bolstered by the fact 
that incomes have become so different and these differences in 
wages and incomes can be as much as 20 or 30 times." 

</TEXT>

