<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Describes Current Economic Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403213994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2051 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1403213994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 14 TASS -- Russian Economic Minister 
Aleksandr Shokhin met U.S. ex-President Richard Nixon on Monday 
to discuss relations between Russia and international 
organizations. 
  Shokhin described some peculiarities of the economic reform 
in Russia at a press conference following the meeting. 
  Acceptance of "the debts of the former Soviet Union, the 
burden of Russia's "donorhood" in regard to other CIS member 
states" make economic transformations in the country peculiar. 
In this connection, he confirmed that the government intends 
"to go ahead with reserved financial policies". 
  "On the one hand, the cabinet succeeded in getting the 
inflation rate down to an all-time low of 9.9 percent, on the 
other - the slump in production continues to grow, which results 
in a drop in efficacy of tax extraction as a whole," Shokhin 
said as he described contradictory nature of the current 
situation in Russia. 
  According to Shokhin, the government will "find it hard to 
keep within the planned limits of the budget deficit", unless it 
takes "extraordinary measures and looks for new sources of 
income". When working out the draft budget, "several 
expenditure items should be specified, including national 
defence expenses", Shokhin said. 

</TEXT>

