<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian TV, Radio To Revert to Old Place-Names </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1303164494 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1520 GMT 
12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1303164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As you know, the process of the disintegration of 
the USSR and sovereignization of the republics within Russia was 
accompanied by a forced introduction to the Russian language of 
new names of some states, republics, their capitals, and some 
cities. At the same time, in most cases it was an attempt to 
replace the names adopted in the Russian language with the names 
in the languages of these states, republics, and cities. 
However, in any language any borrowed word is always 
subordinated to new grammar and pronunciation laws and, in 
practice, never retains its original form. 
  Therefore Russian language speakers have as many rights to 
pronounce Ashkhabad, Kushka, Kirgizia, and Belorussia, as 
speakers of other languages, for example, have every right to 
use Russian names in the form adopted in their languages. In 
this particular case it is correspondence to linguistic laws 
that is under discussion. 
  The Institute of Russian Language of the Russian Academy of 
Sciences supports the intention to go back to old names. From 
15 March, Russian television and radio will begin using them 
consistently so that from now on Almaty will again become 
Alma-Ata, Bashkortostan -- Bashkiria. Our congratulations to 
you. 
  It would be interesting to know what will be the reaction at 
the Ostankino TV and Radio Company since this initiative comes 
from the Russian TV and Radio Company. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

