<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Drops Debate on Chechnya From Agenda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403165094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1406 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1403165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Council of the Russian State Duma at a session 
on Monday dropped from the agenda of the lower house of 
parliament the question of the situation in Chechnya. This was 
reported to journalists by the head of a parliamentary group and 
State Minister for Nationalities Sergey Shakhray. 
  He said Communists, Liberal-Democrats, Democrats and the 
Agrarian Party voted against the debate as they felt the matter 
should be settled by the president himself. "These groups are 
either afraid of Dudayev, or of a controversy about the matter", 
Shakhray announced. 
  Shakhray came out with the initiative of discussing the 
matter in both houses of the Federal Assembly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

