<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev: CIS More Independent, Active </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603131694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1144 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Commonwealth of Independent States is becoming 
more independent and active, Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev said in Moscow Wednesday, opening the meeting of the CIS 
Council of Foreign Ministers. 
  He believes the meeting's agenda reflects this tendency by 
including all key issues ranging from the protection of human 
rights to the protection of borders, more efficient 
peace-keeping operations and the prevention of regional 
conflicts. "Clearly, none of us will solve these problems. We 
should do so only within the framework of the Community on the 
basis of equality and mutual respect," he said. 
  Kozyrev believes that there is no need to speak about the 
international recognition of the Commonwealth of Independent 
States. "We need no international recognition. It is enough to 
have the decision of our presidents and parliaments for the CIS 
to work on and occupy a worthy place in the world. We should 
only speak about the development of CIS contacts with other 
international structures," he said. 
  At the meeting CIS foreign ministers plan to discuss the 
draft convention on the protection of the rights of national, 
ethnic, and religious minorities and the possible creation of a 
standing consultative commission for peacekeeping activities 
under the CIS Council of Foreign Ministers, diplomatic sources 
have told Interfax. 
  The Ministers intend to coordinate a plan of multilateral 
inter-ministry consultations within the CIS framework for 1994. 
They are also to discuss a CIS-CSCE cooperation. 
  The Ministers will have their say on the NATO program 
"Partnership for Peace." 
  In addition, the issue of talks between Russia and the 
Caucasian and Central Asian states on cooperation with the third 
countries on the protection of borders. 
  The Ministers will discuss Kazakhstan's proposal on a 
special 
session of the UN General Assembly on problems of the 
post-confrontation age. 
  Also to be discussed are the steps for the division of 
civilian sea vessels of the ex-Soviet Union between the CIS 
countries and the Baltic states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16320 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov051cc_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-051 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgian, Ukrainian Ministers on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603110594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1050 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 16 TASS -- "The Commonwealth of 
Independent States is acquiring a new quality. Today's agenda 
reflects this trend," Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev 
said in his opening address at the meeting of CIS foreign 
ministers in Moscow today. 
  The forum is being attended by delegations from all 12 
countries of the Commonwealth, including foreign ministers of 
Russia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, Tajikistan and Kazakhstan. Other 
countries are represented by ambassadors and deputy foreign 
ministers. 
  Georgian Foreign Minister Aleksandr Chikvaidze told 
ITAR-TASS 
that a Georgian delegation was taking part in a meeting such as 
this for the first time, but as a new member of the CIS, Georgia 
"will try to make its modest contribution to the strengthening 
of the Commonwealth". 
  Ukrainian Ambassador Vladimir Kryzhanovskiy told ITAR-TASS 
that "We have certain considerations concerning the documents 
examined at the forum, particularly the document on the rights 
of ethnic, religious and linguistic minorities. We do not 
understand what a linguistic minority means. In our republic 
there are ethnic minorities -- Russians and Poles. Ukraine is 
doing everything in its power for them not to feel that their 
rights are infringed upon." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16321 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov051cc_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-051 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agenda for Meeting Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603120994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1137 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By unidentified ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 16 TASS -- An ITAR-TASS correspondent 
has learned that the agenda of the current Commonwealth of 
Independent States (CIS) foreign ministers' meeting here 
includes the following ten items: 
  -- a draft convention on the insurance of the rights of the 
members of ethnic, linguistic and religious minorities, 
  -- the establishment of a standing consultative commission 
on 
peacemaking activities, 
  -- a 1994 plan for multilateral consultations among CIS 
foreign ministries, 
  -- international recognition of the CIS and its statutory 
bodies (interaction between the CIS and the CSCE, and NATO's 
Partnership-for-Peace programme are to be considered within the 
framework of this item), 
  -- the state of affairs at the talks between the Russian 
Federation, Central Asian and Transcaucasian states on 
cooperation in the guarding of their borders with third 
countries, 
  -- a declaration of the observance of the sovereignty, 
territorial integrity and inviolability of CIS countries' 
borders, 
  -- Kazakhstan's proposal to hold a special session of the 
United Nations General Assembly on the problems of the 
post-confrontation era, 
  -- measures to settle the question of dividing the state-run 
non-military ships of the former Soviet Union among CIS and 
Baltic states, 
  -- the drafting of a text of a joint address by CIS 
countries 
to the CIS peoples and the world public opinion in view of the 
50th anniversary of the victory in the Second World War, 
  -- the determination of a date and venue for a regular 
meeting of the foreign ministers of CIS countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

