<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Statement on Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603114994 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1000 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Lithuanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Lithuanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs says that 
all the most important political and economic interests of 
Lithuania were included in the draft Lithuanian-Polish treaty. 
  The statement issued yesterday notes that discussions 
concerning the Lithuanian-Polish treaty on friendly relations 
and good-neighborly cooperation, which is due to be signed, 
often acquire the nature of unilateral accusations. 
  The concern by the Ministry of Foreign affairs was caused by 
a statement issued by a group of Kaunas City Council deputies 
which categorically demands that the text of the draft treaty be 
made public and even points out which concepts should be 
included into the text of the draft treaty. 
  The Ministry of Foreign Affairs said that the negotiations 
with Poland were proceeding according to the principles of 
international law and practice and according to the decision of 
1992 adopted by the government of Lithuania, which says that 
information about negotiations with foreign countries up until 
the signing of the agreement is a state secret of the Republic 
of Lithuania. 
  The Lithuanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs rejects any such 
pressure as an attempt to influence the course of negotiations 
and to complicate mutual relations of the two states. As is 
known, in a democratic country confidence in the quality of work 
of the diplomatic service is tested and verified during the 
ratification of the signed treaty in parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

