<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ardzimba, Envoy on Parliament Disbandment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503202794 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1600 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1503202794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks recorded] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] Abkhazia is stopping its peace talks 
with Georgia. Vladislav Ardzinba, the leader of the autonomy, 
says that the decision is due to the fact that the Georgian 
Supreme Council -- quite illegally, in his opinion -- has 
declared the supreme legislative body of the former autonomous 
republic disbanded. 
  [Ardzinba] "The Law on State Power in the Republic of 
Georgia, to which the Georgian Supreme Council refers as the 
legal foundation for its decision, was adopted unilaterally 
after the state and legal relations between Abkhazia and Georgia 
were terminated. In view of this, it cannot apply to events 
taking place on the territory of the Republic of Abkhazia." 
  [Announcer] This is how Valeriy Advadze, the Georgian 
ambassador to Moscow, commented on Ardzinba's statement at our 
request. 
  [Advadze] "This unilateral decision -- well, it is being 
applied to Abkhazia and the Supreme Soviet of Abkhazia that was 
elected on the basis of a discriminatory law when 17 to 18 
percent of the electorate had 28 seats in parliament, whereas 50 
percent of the Georgian population had 26 seats. I do not think 
another such discriminative law exists anywhere in the world -- 
this is simply impossible. Therefore, the fact that this law 
was made invalid, together with the Supreme Soviet elected on 
the basis of this law, is simply a belated measure. It should 
not have been adopted in the first place, or it should have been 
removed earlier." 
  [Announcer] I would like to point out, however, that 
Georgian 
leader Eduard Shevardnadze considers the decision of the 
Georgian Supreme Council to disband the Abkhazian Supreme Soviet 
a rash measure. 
  Also today, Vladislav Ardzinba spoke sharply against the UN 
peacekeeping troops being introduced in the republic without the 
consent of the Abkhazian [Ardzinba] "If these troops are 
introduced throughout the territory of Abkhazia in the interest 
of the Georgian side, we will regard this as occupation, as an 
attempt to occupy the territory of Abkhazia, with all the 
ensuing consequences. I do not think there is any need to say 
anything else." 
  [Announcer] Valeriy Advadze, the Georgian ambassador to 
Moscow, comments again. 
  [Advadze] "The peacekeeping troops, if they do come, should 
be deployed on the entire territory of Abkhazia so as to insure 
that the residents who fled from there, the refugees, can return 
and to guarantee a normal life and safety for them when they 
return. It cannot be otherwise." 
  [Announcer] This evening the Russian Foreign Ministry 
expressed its concern over the developments in Abkhazia and the 
emergence of a real threat of armed clashes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

