<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Advadze Denies Moscow-Washington `Wedge' Claims </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503172794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1404 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Georgian ambassador in Russia, Valerian Advadze, 
has denied claims by some politicians and the media that the 
recent visit of the Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze to the 
U.S. had the purpose of driving a wedge between Moscow and 
Washington. At a Tuesday news conference in Moscow he stressed 
that the visit did not worsen relations between his country and 
Russia. 
  Commenting on the negative response of the Abkhaz leader 
Vladislav Ardzinba to the plans of sending a peacekeeping force 
to Abkhazia, Advadze said that Russia, the U.S. and the UN "have 
the power to bridle aggressive separatism." According to the 
ambassador, Ardzinba was guided by separatism when he launched 
the war, even though he spoke of Abkhazia's willingness to join 
Russia. The diplomat added that Ardzinba "will not agree to any 
treaties or compromises, he will not be content with any 
federation or confederation, he wants only full independence." 
  The ambassador stressed that the United States and the UN 
Security Council like Russia before them have supported Georgia 
in matters of territorial integrity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

