<F P=102>  LD1503163894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1444 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lyudvig Chibirov, the leader of South Ossetia (a 
self-proclaimed republic in Georgia -- Interfax) said that among 
the priority political problems facing the new parliament is 
holding talks with Georgia to define South Ossetia's political 
status. 
  "We are ready to hold talks at an international level the 
way 
talks between Georgia and Abkhazia are held," he told Interfax 
on Tuesday. 
  As to the idea of uniting South and North Ossetia, supported 
by the population of South Ossetia during the referendum in 
1992, this question will be discussed in Moscow not in 
Tskhinval, he said. 
  North Ossetia is part of Russia. 

