<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Moderate Opposition' Favors Stability Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1503170394 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 15 Mar 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1503170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report of statement by Vladimir Lysenko: </F>
"Moderate Opposition Interested in Stability, State Duma Deputy 
Vladimir Lysenko Believes"] 
  [Text] The recent Kremlin meeting shows that the president 
would really like to sign a memorandum of agreement, but how 
effective would such a document be? I recall that throughout 
the course of last year we had several "roundtables" and some 
very important documents on agreement were signed, but they have 
not been carried out and have had no substantive impact on the 
political situation. Today there is little correlation between 
the authorities and society's political forces. All the changes 
to the power structures have no connection with the situation in 
parliament, with the positions held by political parties, or 
with the demands of the trade unions. That is why the 
opposition undoubtedly has an interest in fundamentally 
resolving the question of power -- that is, winning the 1996 
elections. And, in this sense, a moderate and calm opposition 
could have an interest in some kinds of consensual documents so 
as to buy time and prevent radicals on both flanks from 
destabilizing the situation in the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

