<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray on Restoration of Russian Germans' Autonomy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603010994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1520 
GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603010994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 15 Mar -- The process of the restoration of 
the autonomy of the Germans in Russia is only possible through a 
mass movement "from below" in the places where they live in 
large numbers, thinks Sergey Shakhray, Russian Federation 
minister for nationalities and regional policy. He declared 
this today at a press conference. Sergey Shakhray called such a 
movement "the concept of the self-organization of the Russian 
Germans." 
  In his view, Germans living in our country must, first of 
all, decide for themselves on how to restore their autonomy, 
liaising with the organs of power in the regions where they live 
in large numbers. Only then, he pointed out, will there be a 
real possibility of passing a federal law to that effect. 
  Sergey Shakhray also informed journalists about his recent 
trip to Bonn, where he attended the fifth sitting of the 
Russo-German intergovernmental commission on the problems of the 
Russian Germans. According to the minister, the Russian side 
confirmed its opinion that the Russian Germans can and must 
remain in the Russian Federation. The rights of the Russian 
Germans, repressed in 1941, must be restored. 
  At the sitting of the commission, the minister noted, there 
was discussion of the problems involved in financing the 
restoration of the Russian Germans' autonomy. At present, there 
is no coordination of the sides in this matter, since the 
Germans do not trust our state organizations and pass their part 
of the funds allocated to the implementation of the program 
through private intermediary structures. There are cases of the 
squandering and "disappearance without trace" of the German part 
of the funds. 
  But now, Sergey Shakhray stressed, the sides have agreed 
that, in order to prevent such a situation arising, a special 
Russian-German foundation and, at the local level, 
Russian-German societies will monitor the distribution of funds 
at federal level. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

