<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Breaking Up the FCS' Option for Reorganization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1503191194 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 16 Mar 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1503191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Own Information" report: "A Day In the Life of the Secret </F>
Services: Fiery Hearts Will Set Ministry of Justice Aflame"] 
  [Text] It was announced by a well-informed staffer of the 
Russian Federation Federal Counterintelligence Service [FCS] 
central apparatus that the possibility of breaking up the FCS 
and transferring its functions to other structures is being 
studied in the president's administration as one of the options 
for reorganizing this department. Specifically, it is proposed 
to transfer the FCS Counterintelligence Operations Directorate 
to the Ministry of Justice, transforming it into a Federal 
Bureau of Investigations. The Economic Counterintelligence 
Directorate and the Directorate for Guaranteeing Security at 
Strategically Important Industrial Facilities would be rendered 
subordinate to the Ministry of the Economy, while military 
counterintelligence would be placed under the wings of the 
General Staff as an autonomous directorate. The fight against 
terrorism will switch to the competence of the Ministry of 
Internal Affairs. The author of the plan for eliminating the 
FCS is a member of the Security Council. 
  Our correspondent met with new FCS Chief Sergey Stepashin 
and 
asked him to explain his future plans at this post. The FCS 
chief reported that very soon he will hold a meeting with the 
Russian president. He did not deny reports that Boris Yeltsin 
has been in receipt of suggestions for reorganizing this 
service, including transferring its powers to other departments. 
"If these suggestions are implemented, the security organs will 
be dealt a major blow. I am categorically against this, and I 
am against anybody who puts such suggestions forward. It is 
necessary to ponder why they are doing this. I am deeply 
convinced that Russia and the president need strong secret 
services. And it is this stance which I will be defending at 
the meeting with Yelstin," Stepashin declared. 

</TEXT>

