<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Denies FCS Director's Illness </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503175994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1656 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A senior source at Russia's Federal 
Counterintelligence Service (FSK) [FCS] has denied media reports 
that FSK Director Sergey Stepashin went into hospital after 
meeting President Boris Yeltsin on March 11. 
  "Our life is full of rumors," Aleksandr Mikhailov, head of 
the FSK Public Relations Center, told Interfax on Tuesday. "In 
this particular case an elegant form was found to make gossip 
sound official, with some kind of source being cited `who asked 
not to be identified.'" 
  "Yes, Stepashin did have a meeting on March 11, but with 
Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin and not with the president," 
Mikhailov continued. "Neither that meeting nor [Stepashin's] 
telephone conversation with Yeltsin could have given the FSK 
director any cause for concern. Mood is not always a reason to 
see a doctor anyway." 
  Mikhailov said Stepashin was currently at work. 

</TEXT>

