<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rostelekom Refuses Radio, TV Companies Orders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503182594 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1700 GMT 
15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1503182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the beginning of this month the All-Russia 
Television and Radio Company was given notice by Mr. Belov, 
general director of the Rostelekom joint-stock company, that the 
acceptance and processing of orders for the provision of 
intercity and international television and sound broadcasting 
channels would be suspended from 15 March. 
  This means that Russian television and radio are unable to 
have good-quality and stable communications with their 
correspondents in any of the regions of our country. The 
management of the Russian Television and Radio Company has held 
intensive talks with Russian Communications Minister Vladimir 
Bulgak, who gave the assurance that there would be no 
disconnection from communications channels. 
  Today, however, the Rostelekom joint-stock company refused 
to 
accept and deal with orders from television and radio companies, 
citing a directive from the joint-stock company's management. 
All attempts today to talk to the Russian communications 
minister have been unsuccessful, although, according to our 
information, he had received information about the desperate 
plight in which radio and television find themselves yet again. 
  It seems that today the language of the ultimatum is the 
only 
way in which Russian communications workers can voice their 
interests. 

</TEXT>

