<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Adviser Opposes Economic State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603103394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1012 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 16 TASS -- Aleksandr Livshits, leader 
of a group of experts to the president of Russia, is against the 
passage of bills on an economic state of emergency and on the 
restoration of administrative mechanisms of management, 
including a wage freeze. 
  In a statement received by ITAR-TASS on Wednesday [16 
March], 
Livshits admits that "the Federal Assembly, of course, has the 
right to determine legislative work priorities". However, 
Livshits, dr. of science (economics), is of the opinion that 
"the Russian economy is now in need of a legislative basis for a 
market economy, not a state of emergency which would not resolve 
a single deep-seated problem". 
  Livshits also points out that "the government, basing itself 
on the presidential message to the Federal Assembly, must 
energetically implement its programme and monitor the situation. 
The government should not be pulled about and rendered 
panicky," he emphasises. 
  The presidential message determines a reform strategy and 
basic guidelines for domestic and foreign policies. "No such 
thing as an economic state of emergency is spelled out there," 
the presidential adviser noted. 
  "The president makes active efforts in a quest for national 
concord. Any actions of the Federal Assembly in this respect 
will find understanding and support. But concord does not mean 
a renunciation of reform or a rollback to unjustified emergency 
measures," Livshits stressed. 

</TEXT>

