<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Ills Facing Fuel, Energy Complex Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503165994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1626 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Ivantsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 15 TASS -- Some 16,000,000,000,000 
rubles worth of consumer debt to the Russian fuel and energy 
complex was registered in early February as compared to 
12,000,000,000,000 rubles on January 1, 1994. This debt is half 
of all non-payments in the Russian economy. 
  Russian Fuel and Energy Minister Yuriy Shafranik told 
parliament hearings on non-payments today that the fuel and 
energy situation is most complicated and fraught with grave 
consequences for both the complex and the whole economy. 
  A reason for this is insufficient circulating assets of 
enterprises, imperfection of the legislation and low financial 
discipline of consumers, said Shafranik. 
  In his opinion, it is necessary to adopt a decree on 
regulated payments for fuel and energy in order to ensure severe 
sanctions against the non-payers and their priority payments for 
the supplies. Off-setting of mutual obligations of the budget 
and fuel and energy enterprises, as well as the transfer of the 
2,500,000,000,000 ruble debt of Commonwealth states to the 
complex's account will help settle the problem as well. 
  Experts believe 1,500,000,000,000 rubles worth of 
allocations 
and off-setting of mutual debts worth 5,000,000,000,000 rubles 
would be enough to remove financial tension in the fuel and 
energy complex. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

