<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Outlines Economic Problems in Armed Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603130494 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1100 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Russia's Defense Minister Pavel Grachev held a news 
conference today. He said that a criticial situation has arisen 
as regards financing the Armed Forces. Thus, in January of this 
year, the Defense Ministry received only 63 percent of the 
planned appropriations. Pavel Grachev stated that if in the 
very near future the situation does not improve there cannot be 
any question of any reforming of the Army or of maintaining its 
high combat effectiveness. He said that this year the Army 
would in real terms be cut by 200,000 men instead of the 
scheduled 400,000. The reason for this is that it is more 
expensive to discharge an officer than to keep him -- each 
officer being discharged needs to be simultaneously paid 20 
monthly wages. This year purchases of armaments will be 
considerably reduced. This could have a deplorable effect on 
the defense industry enterprises and the development of new 
military technologies. Pavel Grachev strongly criticized the 
way trade in Russian arms is being conducted: He believes that 
opportunities to earn billions of rubles are being missed. 
  The journalists also inquired how the Army would react to a 
possible increase in social tension in the country. Grachev 
said that the armed forces are outside politics, but would not 
permit a civil war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

