<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets Speaks on Defense Budget Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1503155394 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 15 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1503155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Yermolin report: "Oleg Soskovets Is Opposed to </F>
Further Reducing the Defense Budget"] 
  [Text] The news conference which Oleg Soskovets, first 
deputy chairman of the Russian Federation Government, held 
Monday inaugurates a series of meetings between members of the 
government and journalists. 
  Among the problems facing the Cabinet of Ministers today 
Oleg 
Soskovets named "the state's participation in the country's 
economic development, the improvement of tax policy, the 
elimination of nonpayments, and the social thrust of reforms." 
The government is particularly concerned at the situation in 
the social sphere, in agriculture, and in the 
military-industrial complex. According to Soskovets, a complex 
situation is taking shape in the military-industrial complex 
today. Economic ties between enterprises have been ruptured by 
ill-considered conversion, and in some places the defense 
industry's scientific and production potential has been 
seriously undermined. 
  A further reduction in the defense budget could lead to the 
total stoppage of production facilities working for the needs of 
defense. Reducing expenditure on the Armed Forces means 
"freezing" the further course of reforms and of structural 
restructuring in the Russian Army. As Oleg Soskovets said, the 
government is drawing up measures to encourage production in the 
sphere of the military-industrial complex. In particular, 
conditions are being created for emerging onto the foreign 
market and expanding the defense industry's export potential. 
  As regards the state budget as a whole for 1994, in Oleg 
Soskovets' opinion the revenue part has not been worked out 
here. For example, the planned revenue from privatization has 
been understated. But the budget will be finalized in the 
government as early as this week, and the document will be 
submitted to the State Duma committees. At present the budget 
deficit stands at 9.9 percent. 
  The government is concerned at the social stratification of 
society, which is unprecedented on the scale of modern civilized 
countries, when approximately 30 percent of the population is 
living below the poverty line, while the incomes of another 
section of Russians are growing inordinately. At the same time 
commercial activity is most lucrative, as distinct from activity 
in the sphere of physical production. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

