<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets on Readiness to Trade Defensive Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403150794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1215 
GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1403150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 14 Mar -- The Russian Federation has the 
most up-to-date defensive weapons systems, it is willing to 
trade with them, and weapons made in Russia can ensure the 
security and sovereignty of any state. Such are the remarks 
made by Oleg Soskovets, a first deputy chairman of the Russian 
Federation Government, on the pages of an issue of the VOYENNYY 
PARAD journal issued here. 
  Viktor Glukhikh, the chairman of the state committee for 
defense sectors, analyzes the state of Russia's 
military-industrial sector. He notes, in particular, that the 
volume of production of arms and military equipment in Russia in 
1993 was only 47.8 percent of the 1991 level. Over that period, 
the production of aircraft and helicopters dropped by a factor 
of 3.8, armored tank equipment by over four-fifths, ammunition 
by a factor of 4.5, and military production in the electronics 
industry by a factor of 5.4. The main reason for the drop in 
the pace of military production is the lack of financing. At 
the end of 1993, the state owed the military industry about one 
trillion rubles for already manufactured products. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

