<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shaposhnikov Assesses State of Defense Industries </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503170394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1616 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: Compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov and Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Yevgeniy Shaposhnikov, the president's 
representative in the Razoruzheniye (Disarmament) state owned 
company (and former commander of the joint CIS forces), told 
Interfax that if Russia's defense industries continue to be 
neglected as they are now, a political party could be set up 
which would lobby for the industries. This idea was advanced at 
a recent conference of the industries. 
  Shaposhnikov did not object to cuts in military spending but 
said that "the principles of sufficient reason as well as 
reasonable sufficiency" had to be observed. 
  In his view, the proposed cut (to less than one fifth of the 
1993 figure) of spending for military contracts might harm the 
scientific and industrial potential of the country. 
Shaposhnikov thought that the rocketry, air force and other 
services using high technologies could be the worst hit. 
  In a more intelligent approach, Shaposhnikov thought, "the 
number of design boards and factories specializing in 
development and manufacture of the same products" could be cut. 
This kind of competition would make it possible to preserve and 
consolidate the most efficient producers while less fortunate 
competitors could turn to other activities, probably for 
peaceful purposes. 
  The defense industries must have better guidelines, he 
thought. Four specific state programs had to be adopted, of 
weapons production, reduction and utilization of non-promising 
production lines, conversion to peaceful uses and weapons export. 
  "Even though I am with a mediator organization engaged in 
sales of weapons, I don't think it fair that military hardware 
producers cannot participate in exporting their products. They 
must have the right of direct access to the world market so as 
to enable them to use part of their proceeds for their immediate 
needs and increase the national budget revenue by paying taxes," 
Shaposhnikov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

