<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Arms Sale Company To Be `State Monopoly' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403213394 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1800 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1403213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Reform continues in the country. Today, the state 
company for the export and import of arms, Rosvooruzheniye 
[Russian Arms], held a presentation for journalists. The former 
USSR never traded in arms, but simply delivered them according 
to agreements. So there has only been trade proper since 1991. 
But in this sphere, liberalization has led to a situation where 
dozens of Russian firms are tendering for contracts to supply 
India with artillery shells, all selling the product of the same 
factory. And the one who got the contract was the one who 
knocked down his price one and one-half times. 
  By setting up Rosvooruzheniye, the government has created a 
state monopoly on arms trading. But this does not mean that 
enterprises are deprived of the opportunity to be involved in 
foreign trade -- simply that this is now done under the guidance 
of, or, to be more precise, while observing Rosvooruzheniye's 
price controls. One of the company's main activities will be 
investment of profits from promising research work -- at present 
3-5 percent of the value of a contract. It will also receive 
additional income, where the latter has been successful. The 
arms trade is a subtle business. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

