<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies New Cosmodrome Planned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503172194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1404 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A senior official of the Russian Space Agency (RSA) 
in an interview with INTERFAX has described as groundless a 
recent statement by Commander of Military Space Forces (MSF) 
General Vladimir Ivanov about Moscow's plans to build a new 
cosmodrome (space center) in the Far East by the year 2000. 
  He said that building such a facility was not MSF's job but 
that of a special branch of the industry which is in Ukraine and 
elsewhere after the break-up of the Soviet Union. 
  On the prospect of a Far Eastern project, the RSA official 
said that although his agency had no objections, billions of 
rubles would have to be raised to implement it by the year 2000, 
something that Moscow could not afford at the moment. 

</TEXT>

