<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Plan To Join Ruble Zone `Speculation' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503153994 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 11 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1503153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Statement by the Ukrainian Presidential and Cabinet of </F>
Ministers Press Service"; date not given] 
  [Text] Some Ukrainian and foreign (predominantly Russian) 
mass media have recently carried abundant information on the 
Crimean leadership's declared orientation toward Crimea's 
joining the "ruble zone" and even on the accord on this matter 
allegedly reached between Kiev and Simferopol. In reality, 
however, such assertions are nothing more than political 
speculation. 
  Questions of granting the Crimea the most extensive economic 
powers will be discussed. Regarding the question of state 
financial policy, including the introduction of a particular 
currency regime, it is exclusively the jurisdiction of Ukraine's 
state organs, not of individual administrative and territorial 
formations. This is, in particular, stressed in Ukraine's 
Supreme Council decree of 24 February 1994 "On the Status of the 
Crimean Autonomous Republic in Accordance With Ukraine's Current 
Constitution and Legislation." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

