<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Weapons Sales Data in Military Reduction Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1503151894 Lvov POST-POSTUP in Ukrainian 10-16 Mar 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> WS1503151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Lvov POST-POSTUP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Data on Ukrainian Weapons Trade in </F>
1993"] 
  [Text] The number of conventional weapons that remained on 
Ukrainian soil after the breakup of the Soviet Union had to be 
reduced in three stages. Between 1991 and 1993, 25 percent of 
all weapons -- 531 tanks, 422 infantry vehicles, and 140 
aircraft -- had to be eliminated. 
  In 1993, the total export of weapons abroad stood at $29 
million, while the total export of goods -- at $5.508 billion 
[as published]. The specific proportion of weapons exported as 
part of total exports is 25 percent. 
  As for Ukraine, it sold tanks to Slovakia and Russia for the 
sum of $575,000; aircraft, including satellites and 
missile-carriers, for $5,199,000, and radio guidance equipment 
for $3,651,000. In addition, military and rescue vessels were 
sold to Russia and Greece for a total of $721,000. Bombs, 
grenades, torpedoes, missiles, and cartridges made up the 
greatest portion of military exports ($9,772,000). Ukraine 
sold ships as scrap-iron to Turkey, Russia, and Britain for 
$579,000. 
  It is difficult to comment on the benefits of this trade for 
Ukraine, because there is no official data on the total amount 
of weapons traded. We learned from sources close to the 
president that Ukraine sold 80 tanks. We know that the latest 
model T-80T, which is being produced in Kharkov, costs more than 
$2 million. The cost of this tank as scrap-iron is $4,000 (one 
tonne of scrap-iron sells for $100). 
  We would like to add that in 1992, the Commercial Center 
within the Ukrainian Defense Ministry traded 13 military vessels 
as scrap-iron. The Ukrainian state coffers received only 5 
percent from the sale of this scrap-iron. The Commercial Center 
was later disbanded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

