<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Agrees To Resume Talks With Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1503175694 Tallinn Ministry of Foreign Affairs Press 
Release in English 1630 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1503175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Ministry of Foreign Affairs Press 
Release </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Immediate release" from the Estonian Ministry of Foreign </F>
Affairs in Tallinn dated 15 March: "Estonia Accepts April Date 
for Next Round of Talks With Russia; Asks European Union To 
Mediate Under European Stability Pact"] 
  [Text] The eighteenth round of Estonian-Russian 
negotiations will take place in Moscow April 5-6. Despite 
numerous difficult to explain statements made by Russian leaders 
regarding the breaking off of talks and the postponing of the 
agreed-upon date for final withdrawal, Estonia decided yesterday 
to accept the April date offered by Russia for the 18th round of 
talks. 
  At the last round, held March 1-2 outside Tallinn, Russia 
backed away from August 31, 1994, the agreed upon date for final 
withdrawal of the 2,600 ex-Soviet troops remaining in Estonia. 
In addition, Russia demanded further conditions for withdrawal 
and did not propose a date for the next round. 
  International reaction to Russia's moves was swift and 
strong, unanimously supporting Estonia's contention that Russian 
troops must leave, unconditionally, by August 31. Western 
reaction played an important role in Russia's current decision 
to continue the talks and to abide by the withdrawal date. 
  Estonian negotiating team leader, Ambassador Vaeino Reinart, 
began consultations in Brussels today. He will call upon the 
European Union to help mediate Estonian-Russian negotiations 
within the framework of the European Stability Pact. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

