<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ostankino's `Provocative Report' Criticized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1503174594 Yerevan Radio Yerevan International Service in 
Armenian 2000 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1503174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Radio Yerevan International Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Armenian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The news program of Moscow's Ostankino Television 
aired yet another provocative report on 13 March that was 
probably submitted by the Azerbaijani side. This is always the 
case whenever the conflicting sides come close to an agreement 
on a cease-fire and the commencement of talks. 
  Before reporting on the meeting between Babken Ararktsyan, 
chairman of Armenian Supreme Council, and Rasul Guliyev, 
chairman of the Azerbaijani Supreme Soviet, at the 
Idzhevanskiy-Kazakhskiy border on 12 March, the announcer stated 
that the Armenian side was forced to halt military operations 
because of losses it recently suffered in Karabakh. 
  This is an absolute lie because the Nagorno-Karabakh 
Republic 
and Armenia have always proposed a cease-fire and talks. The 
claim about Armenian defeats is also a lie. The only success by 
the Azerbaijani side since the start of the offensive on 18 
December 1993 was that they penetrated Kelbadzharskiy Rayon. 
However, they suffered considerable losses and were forced out. 
The Azerbaijanis have always suffered defeats and have lost 
tens of thousands of men on the other war fronts too. 
  During his interview, Rasul Guliyev said that the Armenian 
forces must be withdrawn from all Azerbaijani lands. 
  This has always been Azerbaijan's aspiration. However, the 
opposing side has never agreed to it, and no such agreement was 
concluded during the aforementioned meeting. This was confirmed 
by Babken Ararktsyan in his statement to Mayak Radio following 
the report on Ostankino. In refuting that report and in an 
attempt to avoid similar intrigues by the Azerbaijani side, the 
chairman of the Armenian Supreme Council declared that 
henceforth Armenia will not go to such meetings unless the 
Karabakh side also takes part in them. 
  Babken Ararktsyan spoke in detail about this meeting in his 
news conference today. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

