<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nomenklatura Win Feared in Altay Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1603102594 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 15 Mar 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM1603102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "First Results"] </F>
  [Excerpts] Elections to representative state power bodies 
within the Council of the Federation were held in five regions 
of Russia on Sunday. They were declared valid in the majority 
of districts. According to preliminary figures, sufficient 
numbers of voters went to the polls in 35 of the 47 districts in 
the Chuvash Republic. 
  The elections were declared valid in 34 out of 50 districts 
in Altay. 
  In Khabarovsk Kray, the corresponding figure is 23 out of 25 
districts. 
  In Kostroma Oblast, elections were validated in 14 out of 15 
oblasts. 
  In the Jewish Autonomous Oblast the figure is 11 out of 15 
districts. 
  The Central Electoral Commission announced that more precise 
figures will be known tomorrow. [passage omitted] 
<H5>  Altay Kray </H5>
  The experience of having government members become deputies 
and switch to work in the State Duma without leaving their 
government posts is evidently going to be repeated in Altay. By 
far, the greatest number of candidates for the Kray legislative 
assembly registered here were administration heads or directors. 
According to legal experts, if the elections end in their favor 
the principle of the division of powers expounded in the 
Constitution will thereby be violated. After all, the job of 
the majority of contenders for the kray legislative assembly is 
to resolve economic problems, while the functions of the 
representative power consist of adopting laws and monitoring 
administration activity, whereas administration heads and 
leaders of all ranks involved in the executive structures are 
going to start adopting laws, so to speak, "to suit themselves." 
It is not difficult to guess where this could lead. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

