<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   CCP Head Foresees `All-out War' in North Caucasus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503162394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1135 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tension is mounting in the North Caucasus, Musa 
Shanibov, president of the Confederation of Caucasian Peoples 
(CCP) told INTERFAX. In his view, local conflicts could grow 
into an all-out war throughout that region. 
  Shanibov feared that a Kabardino-Balkarian problem might 
emerge on top of the Abkhazian, Ossetian-Ingush, Chechen and 
Ossetian-Georgian troubles. He accused Sergey Filatov, the 
Russian president's chief of staff, of having inspired the 
decree on steps to rehabilitate the Balkarian people issued by 
Valeriy Kokov, the president of the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic 
(KBR). The decree called for reinstatement of two Balkarian 
districts that had been abolished in 1944. Shanibov felt that 
the decree might revive KBR's territorial claims on parts of 
Northern Ossetia and the Stavropol Territory. 
  On the other hand, Shanibov believed that those who did not 
want war and supported Abkhazia and the CCP to an extent were 
gaining influence in the Russian leadership. 
  He said that the CCP intended to establish contacts with the 
West and international organizations with a view to obtaining 
their aid in resolving the North Caucasian problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

