<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Views Law on Economic State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503175694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1656 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaker of the State Duma (the lower house of 
parliament) Ivan Rybkin has reaffirmed a statement from his 
counterpart of the upper house Vladimir Shumeyko saying the two 
of them had discussed the possibility of adopting a law on a 
state of emergency in the country's economy on Tuesday. 
  In an interview with Interfax, he said Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin was also involved in discussion about delays in 
adopting this year's budget. Rybkin said although the budget 
bill should have been discussed by the Duma in January, the 
government would table it only next week. "This means the Duma 
will be unable to approve a budget for the second quarter of 
this year", he said. 
  Rybkin said that three possible options of adopting the 
budget were discussed. One is a special law. Next, the 
suspension of some articles of the law on emergency measures. 
And finally, to go on as usual, in which case, he said "we will 
need at least two or three months to approve the budget which 
means a repeat of the situation of 1992-1993 when Russia had to 
survive without a budget". 
  However, Rybkin declined to say which of the three options 
was best. "Sometimes it seems that a short cut is the best 
solution. I do not know if that is true. The issue will come 
under discussion by the Duma Council today", he said. 

</TEXT>

