<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Against Lifting Ossetian State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403201994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1746 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1403201994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Minister for Nationalities and Regional 
Policies, Sergey Shakhray, stood against the lifting of the 
state of emergency in the zone of the Ossetian-Ingush conflict 
until the conflicting parties started negotiating. He said the 
lifting of the state of emergency could trigger off a new armed 
conflict and make necessary the introduction of the armed forces 
in the region. Shakhray spoke during the closed parliamentary 
hearings in the Federation Council which discussed settlement of 
the inter-ethnic conflict. According to Shakhray, the state of 
emergency must be preserved, and does not demand significant 
expenses. 
  Shakhray told Interfax that the cost of financing the 
interim 
administration in the conflict zone during 1993 had been put at 
23 Bn rubles. He stressed that the Ingush budget was subsidized 
by 97and the North Ossetian one by 60Both republics 
explained the financing by the necessity to eliminate of the 
conflict's consequences. However, "not a single house has as 
yet been repaired," Shakhray said. 
  According to him, due to the current situation it was 
necessary to resort to economic pressure through use of the 
federal budget. This means that financial aid must be 
conditioned with the holding of negotiations between the 
conflicting parties. The central authorities must help with the 
negotiations and establish the needed guarantees, he emphasized. 
  Shakhray said that during the parliament's meeting he had 
received the impression that the North Ossetian and the Ingush 
presidents were ready to negotiate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

