<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Comments Prior to Christopher Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1603105594 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 16 Mar 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1603105594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Pavel Shinkarenko under "Diplomacy" rubric: </F>
"Andrey Kozyrev and Warren Christopher Are `Filling the Cracks' 
Which Have Appeared in the Edifice of Russian-U.S. Relations"] 
  [Text] Only two months have passed since the meeting 
between Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton, which was successful in 
every respect, but quite a few "cracks" have appeared in the 
edifice of the Russian-U.S. partnership announced in Moscow. 
There has been the Ames espionage "affair," the embarrassment 
over the Moscow visit of ex-President Nixon, Washington's 
emissary, and the different readings of ways to settle the 
Bosnian crisis. Let us add to this the tragedy in the Arab 
mosque in Hebron, which interrupted the process which had begun 
of settling the Arab-Israeli conflict; the problems of the 
Russian-speaking population in the Baltic countries.... 
  As we see, there are quite a few topics to analyze. 
Therefore the latest meeting between the heads of the Russian 
and U.S. foreign policy departments, which took place in 
Vladivostok yesterday, resembled the work of restorers filling 
cracks in the walls of an ancient building. International 
problems were also discussed in passing. Particularly as Andrey 
Kozyrev has just visited the Near East, where he held talks with 
the leaders of Israel and the PLO, while Warren Christopher has 
visited a number of countries in the Asia and Pacific region. 
  At Vnukovo Airport, from where the head of the Russian 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs flew to Vladivostok, Andrey Kozyrev 
remarked in conversation with journalists that there are certain 
circles both in the United States and in Russia which dislike 
cooperation between the two countries, particularly when it 
takes on a strategic nature. Nevertheless, the minister 
believes that Russian-U.S. relations will continue to be based 
on the principles of the Moscow Declaration. "It is a 
strategic, mature partnership, indications of which are a 
commonality of interests and a close level of contacts," he 
emphasized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

