<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Submarines Active Off Russian Coasts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603124994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1144 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Admiral Igor Kasatonov, first deputy commander of 
the Russian Navy, said that even though our former "potential 
enemies have become our partners, their activities off the 
Russian coasts has not reduced." 
  He told INTERFAX that "contacts and even collisions" with 
U.S. submarines off the Russian coasts had been registered last 
year. The submarines were most active off the Kola Peninsula and 
the Russian Far Eastern Maritime Territory. 
  Kasatonov said that "the U.S. subs have not left those 
areas. 
On the contrary, they show vigor and enviable tenacity." 
  According to Russian Navy experts, "foreign countries have 
retained the formations of their surface ships and submarines," 
Kasatonov emphasized. 
  "This compels the Russian military to act so as to protect 
Russia's safety," Kasatonov said. 
  He denied that Russian submarines were prowling off Florida. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

