<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Fears Georgian-Abkhaz Fighting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503174894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1643 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503174894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Aleksandr Krylovich </F>
and Dmitriy Chubarov] 
  [Text] Moscow March 15 TASS -- The Russian Foreign ministry 
expressed grave concern over the danger of fresh armed clashes 
in the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict zone. The Ministry's chief 
spokesman Grigoriy Karasin told a briefing today that 
"Georgian-Abkhazian relations have got exacerbated recently". 
  According to the spokesman, at the latest round of 
Russian-brokered talks on political settlement in Abkhazia, 
which was held under the U.N. auspices in New York on March 7-9, 
the Georgian side threatened "to go back to war path" unless the 
independence-seeking Abkhazia recognized Georgia's territorial 
integrity and agreed to the return of all ethnic Georgian 
refugees. 
  Karasin stressed that the Russian side was taking "a number 
of urgent steps to prevent fresh fighting in Abkhazia and to 
keep the negotiating process going". 
  Russia will also press for a peacekeeping operation in 
Abkhazia to be carried out by the United Nations or with its 
approval and "resting, if need be, on a Russian military 
contingent", the Foreign Ministry spokesman emphasised. 

</TEXT>

