<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details of Latvian Troop Withdrawal Treaty Given </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503165694 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1500 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1503165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] It seems as though Moscow and Riga have at long last 
established common ground over the withdrawal of Russian forces. 
  [Correspondent Vlada Vishnevskaya] Today the heads of the 
state delegations at the Russo-Latvian negotiations, Sergey 
Zotov and Martins Virsis, initialled an agreement on the 
conditions and timetable for the withdrawal of Russian forces 
from Latvian territory, an agreement on social security for 
servicemen in the Russian army, military pensioners and members 
of their families, and a treaty on the temporary functioning of 
the Skrunda radar station. 
  So, the bilateral talks which have been going on for two 
years have entered the concluding stage. The delegations have 
managed to reach agreement on the fundamental question, the 
timetable for the withdrawal of forces. Ten thousand Russian 
servicemen will be withdrawn from Latvia by 31 August this year. 
The problem of the lease payment for the use of the Skrunda 
radar remains unresolved. Russia is offering 2 million dollars, 
but this is not acceptable to the Latvians. However, the 
leaders of the delegations believe that these disagreements 
should not affect the final signing of the agreements which were 
initialled today. The documents may be signed when the Russian 
and Latvian presidents meet. According to the head of the 
Russian delegation, this meeting could take place as early as 
April. 

</TEXT>

