<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Envoy Discusses Stance in North-South Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1603062794 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1200 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1603062794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks recorded] </F>
  [Text] A news conference was held for Russian reporters at 
the DPRK Embassy in Moscow on 14 March. Son Song-pil, DPRK 
ambassador to Russia, spoke at the new conference. He briefed 
Pyongyang's position in connection with the North-South talks 
for the exchange of top-level special envoys. 
  Station reporter (Aleksey Kolony) who attended the news 
conference reports: The DPRK ambassador quoted a DPRK Foreign 
Ministry spokesman's 13 March statement. The statement 
indicates that North-South dialogue held to discuss the issue of 
exchanging top-level special envoys has encountered a serious 
barrier recently. 
  Ambassador Son continued to say: "As you know, in the 
DPRK-U.S. contact held recently, an agreement was reached in 
conducting the four-point joint actions simultaneously. That is 
to say, the two sides agreed to put the four points into action 
simultaneously. They are: First, the United States announces 
the suspension of the Team Spirit joint military exercise. 
Second, we receive an inspection to ensure the continuity of 
safeguards. Third, we hold North-South working-level delegates' 
contact for the exchange of special envoys. Fourth, the DPRK 
and the United States hold the third round of the DPRK-U.S. 
talks." 
  Saying that Pyongyang is ready to abide by all problems 
which 
have already been agreed upon, the DPRK ambassador briefed on 
the current situation in North-South dialogue. 
  [Son] "However, the persons in authority of South Korea, 
unlike the attitude they took in the early days of their 
assumption of power, opposed the exchange of special envoys 
simply because we proposed it. They opposed [words indistinct]. 
However, giving in to our strong demand and the Korean people's 
pressure calling for holding North-South dialogue, they 
reluctantly responded to the working-level contact for the 
exchange of special envoys. 
  Proceeding from our will to create a good atmosphere for the 
realization of the exchange of special envoys, we proposed the 
following four demands at the fourth working-level contact: 
First, the suspension of all large-scale nuclear military 
exercises. Second, the renouncement of the international 
alliance system in connection with our so-called nuclear 
problem. Third, the suspension of the plan to deploy Patriot 
missiles to South Korea. Fourth, the cancellation of the remarks 
by the person in authority in South Korea that he cannot shake 
hands with a counterpart who possesses nuclear weapons. We 
proposed the above because we believed these issues should be 
resolved first in order to provide favorable circumstances for 
the working-level contact on the exchange of special envoys to 
proceed amid an atmosphere of mutual trust between the North and 
the South." 
  In conclusion, responding to the station reporter's question 
about the prospects of the North-South dialogue, DPRK Ambassador 
Son Song-pil said: "Problems seem complicated. However, they 
are actually not complicated. Who complicates problems? It is 
precisely the South Korean authorities and the United States. 
The pressing issue that should be solved between the DPRK and 
the United States at present is the nuclear issue. As I said 
earlier, the South Korean authorities are not in a position to 
edge themselves into this issue. 
  What the U.S. side needs to do is withdraw U.S. nuclear 
bases 
and nuclear weapons from South Korea and renounce its 
large-scale military and nuclear threats and hostile policy 
against us. In return for this, we will receive nuclear 
inspections. Thus, the United States and we should resolve 
problems, and others should not be involved in this. Therefore, 
the issue of solving the nuclear issue through a package 
settlement should be solved first through the talks between the 
United States and us. If the United States removes its nuclear 
weapons from South Korea, thereby removing the nuclear threat 
against us, a package settlement of the nuclear issue will be 
realized and the basic issues between us and the United States 
will be eliminated anyway." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

