<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rutskoy Calls For Restoration of Soviet Union </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603094294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0916 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603094294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 16 TASS -- Former Russian 
Vice-President Aleksandr Rutskoy, in a statement sent to 
ITAR-TASS on the eve of the third anniversary of March 17, 1991, 
referendum, during which most citizens voted for the 
preservation of the Soviet Union, has called for the recreation 
of the erstwhile unity of the former Soviet Union but warned 
this is impossible to do through bloodshed. 
  "Only through indomitable will and fortitude of the 
fraternal 
peoples and a desire to live together, we shall be able to 
attain the cherished goal or we shall get lost one by one," the 
statement said. 
  Rutskoy believes that over the past three years "the reality 
itself proved that the CIS (Commonwealth of Independent States) 
is non-viable" and that "the people have come to realise in full 
the price of the irresponsible and light-minded decision to 
dismantle the Soviet Union". 
  At the same time the former vice-president is convinced it 
is 
impossible to prevent the country "from slipping down into an 
abyss through meetings, demonstrations and irresponsible 
statements that border on a political provocation". 
  Rutskoy considers it necessary to comprehend this and look 
for more effective forms for rapprochement and cooperation in an 
atmosphere of an intensifying disintegration, economic, social 
and political crisis. He did not specify what forms he had in 
mind. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

