<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 17 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703091594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0503 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703091594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 17 (ITAR-TASS) -- The NEZAVISIMAYA 
GAZETA newspaper reports today that a regular meeting of the 
foreign ministers' council of the Commonwealth of Independent 
States (CIS) held in Moscow on Wednesday agreed the most 
important foreign policy issues on the life of the Commonwealth 
and its participation in international affairs. 
  Arguing with advocates of a state of economic emergency in 
Russia, Professor Aleksandr Livshits, head of the Russian 
president's expert group, writes in the TRUD newspaper that 'the 
country needs, among other things, an appropriate law to impose 
a state of economic emergency in the country. 
  'The law would lay down under what conditions the state of 
emergency is imposed, for what period, what measures are being 
enacted and who takes the decision.' Livshits pointed out the 
absence of such a law at present. 
  Therefore, he claims, 'the imposition of a state of economic 
emergency in our country is out of the question.' Noting that 
the Russian parliament should decide what laws should be drafted 
and adopted, the expert stressed the priority need for creating 
a legal basis for reforms. 
  Livshits expressed opinion that 'talks about emergency 
measures are groundless and even undesirable, since they can 
promote destabilization in society.' Describing the present 
situation in the Russian economy as 'difficult', the expert 
stressed that 'the government should keep the situation under 
control, implement the present programs thoughtfully, including 
work on structural reorganization. 
  'On the other hand, a return to administrative mechanisms of 
government and a freeze on prices and wages would lead the 
country to a quick collapse'. 
  Commenting on the treaty between Russia and Tatarstan, 
Nikolay Medvedev, head of the president's office division on 
work with territories, says in an interview with NEZAVISIMAYA 
GAZETA that the treaty is really a qualitatively new basid 
document recording both the delimitation of subjects of 
authority as well as mutual delegation of powers between the 
federation and its member republic. 
  He expressed opinion that the treaty with Tatarstan 'will be 
both a stabilising factor and work done for the country's 
future.' 'We have shown an ability to find the way out of 
really deadlocked situations and what's the main thing -- a 
desire to come to agreement,' Medvedev stressed. 
  In the opinion of the ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI newspaper, ' the 
countryside should not be fenced off with a bureaucratic wall 
from the market. At the same time, peasants should not be 
herded, in 'the bright past'. 
  The newspaper expresses regret in a report from a meeting of 
the government commission on urgent matters that the favorable 
period for the state's timely aid to the countryside has passed. 
  'The state in the person of the finance ministry has turned 
to be unable to return debts in time,' ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI writes, 
noting that the state now owes 1,300 billion rubles to the 
countryside 'for already consumed produce.' 
  Writing in the KRASNAYA ZVEZDA newspaper, Margarita 
Maximova, 
senior researcher of the institute of world economics and 
international relations, claims that only economically strong 
and politically stable Russia can become a driving force for the 
integration of former Soviet republics. 
  Examining versions for cooperation within the Commonwealth, 
the scholar draws the conclusion that discrepancy between the 
interests of Russia and other CIS countries is no barrier to the 
rapprochement. 
  'World experience shows that any interstate alliance was and 
is based, above all, on the balance on interests of its 
participants,' Maximova stresses. 
  Reporting the publication of the book 'The Last Soviet 
Government', the PRAVDA newspaper writes that 'the last the 
ministers of the Soviet Union are convinced that they stepped 
down unvanquished and unhumiliated'. 
  The newspaper features opinions of nine former ministers 
Nikolay Ryzhkov, Leonid Abalkin, Vadim Bakatin and others on 
events in Russia. 
  Under the headline 'Interview with a woman called Soviet 
Jeanne d'Arc', PRAVDA outlines views of former Soviet legislator 
Sazhi Umalatova on the situaion in Russia. 'The people will 
learn to protect their rights later of sooner,' she stresses. 
  Expressing joy over the recent release of inmates for the 
Lefortovo and Matrosskaya Tishina prisons as a result of the 
amnesty proclaimed by parliament, Umalatova stated that 
'Hysteria concerning unpredictable consequences to be caused by 
the amnesty of opposition politicians is not accidental.' 
  'The same 'scenario writers' stir up trouble, trying to 
split 
society and to provoke opposition for drastic actions in order 
to bring tanks back,' she claims. 
  Under the title 'In the Footsteps of Terminator', the 
SOVETYSKAYA ROSSIYA newspaper describes particulars of a 
massacre at a Russian border post on Tanfilev Island (Russian 
Far East), including a commentary by Colonel-General Nikolayev, 
commander-in-chief of Russian Border troops, on this deplorable 
event. 

</TEXT>

