<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nixon Comments on Potential Russian Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1603163194 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 16 Mar 94 
First Edition p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM1603163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "Richard Nixon: There Is No Alternative </F>
To Yeltsin Today"] 
  [Text] There is no alternative to President Boris Yeltsin 
in Russia right now. This was stated to journalists by Richard 
Nixon after his speech at the State Duma committee for 
international affairs. "I held meetings with a number of 
leaders and concluded that right now there is no one who would 
be ready to take his place," the U.S. ex-president stressed. 
"They will appear but for the moment there are no people like 
that," ITAR-TASS reports. 
  Speaking of his meetings with Grigoriy Yavlinskiy and Sergey 
Shakhray, Richard Nixon noted: "They are both young, vigorous, 
and highly educated. I think they can be viewed as potential 
leaders. But I would not rule out others with whom I met. In 
particular I was impressed by the Communists' leader Gennadiy 
Zyuganov. But he will not become president since Russia does 
not intend to return to communism." 

</TEXT>

