<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Supports Russia's Participation in G-7 Meetings </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703112394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703112394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vasiliy Golovnin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo March 17 TASS -- Tokyo believes that Russia's 
official membership of the Group of Seven industrialised 
countries (G-7) should be decided gradually and "naturally" in 
line with the accumulation of positive results of dialogues 
between the leading industrial countries and Russia. 
  This was announced at a meeting between Japan's Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata, who is also deputy prime minister, with 
Russian journalists ahead of his visit to Moscow on March 19. 
  Hata said Italy, which is president of the G-7 meetings this 
year, will decide on inviting Russian President Boris Yeltsin to 
the G-7 summit in Naples and on the form of his participation in 
it. 
  The earlier tested scheme "seven plus one," in accordance 
with which the Russian president has already participated in G-7 
annual meeting, is quite suitable for discussing frankly and 
openly political and economic issues of concern to all, he added. 
  "I consider the fact of Russia's regular participation in 
G-7 
meetings as important," Hata pointed out and stressed that a 
change to the current formula would depend on the results of 
dialogue between Moscow and the leading industrial powers of the 
world. 

</TEXT>

