<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Meets Milosevic, Karadzic, Leaves for Washington </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603181894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1650 
GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603181894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 16 Mar (ITAR-TASS) -- Vitaliy Churkin met 
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic today. The official report 
about the meeting says the two exchanged views on the talks 
process, Russia's initiatives, and the conditions for achieving 
a political settlement in the former Yugoslavia. It was 
stressed that one of the main conditions is that equal account 
be taken of the national and state interests of the sides drawn 
into the conflict and that mediation by international 
representatives be impartial. 
  Churkin also met Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic. The 
sides described the meeting as "a continuation of working 
contacts with a high level of mutual understanding." Karadzic 
expressed his satisfaction with the fact that when the issue of 
a Muslim-Croatian federation in Bosnia was being discussed, the 
Russian side had made it quite clear that the Bosnian Serbs have 
the same sovereign rights as the Muslims and Croats. For the 
Bosnian Serbs, close relations with Yugoslavia are crucial, so 
we have to look for a way towards a settlement that takes 
account of this interest, Karadzic said. 
  Churkin left Belgrade today. He said he was going to 
Washington to hold consultations about the Yugoslav problem with 
the U.S. President's special representative Charles Redman. 

</TEXT>

