<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Leader Says Referendum To Be Held Despite Ban </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603180894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1638 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Crimean referendum on relations with Ukraine 
scheduled for 27 March will be held despite Kiev's ban, Crimean 
President Yuriy Meshkov told INTERFAX on Wednesday. 
  Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk issued a decree late on 
Tuesday [15 March] to ban the Crimean poll because of its being 
out of line with the Ukrainian Constitution and laws. 
  The Crimean referendum ordered by Meshkov is designed to 
elicit an answer to two questions. One is on relations between 
Simferopol and Kiev and the other on dual citizenship. 
  Meshkov said that such questions "are to be decided locally 
and not by Kiev" warning against attempts to try to deprive the 
public of its right to freedom of expression. 
  He said that an administrative ban was an on-off affair 
because the referendum issue might resurface within a week or a 
month again. 
  "There is a body of opinion which Kiev may find more useful 
to know of than Simferopol", Meshkov said adding that he saw no 
reason for further discussion on that score. 

</TEXT>

