<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Signs Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603192394 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1800 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1603192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Mircea Snegur has signed in Brussels the 
document on the Republic of Moldova's adherence to the 
Partnership for Peace [PFP] program. 
  As our press correspondent, Andrei Barsan, reported in his 
speech given after the signing of the framework document, NATO 
General Secretary Manfred Woerner emphasized that by joining the 
PFP concept, the Republic of Moldova demonstrates that it shares 
the main objective pursued by the Alliance: Building a European 
order of peace that is based on the principles of democracy and 
human rights. 
  Referring to problems in the east of Moldova, Manfred 
Woerner 
said that the Alliance supports a rapid and complete withdrawal 
of foreign troops from that area and hopes that a rapid peaceful 
solution may be found in connection with the said problems. 
  In turn, President Mircea Snegur said that, as a trustworthy 
partner, Moldova will strengthen its bilateral relations with 
Central and East European countries and will cooperate honestly 
with the Euro-Atlantic security structures in accordance with 
the PFP principles and objectives. 
  We pay special attention to the mechanism of consultations 
on 
security stipulated by the PFP, particularly when a 
participating state believes that it is facing a direct threat 
against its territorial integrity, political independence, and 
national security. This is all the more important since the 
said principles are questioned today by the presence of foreign 
troops on the territory of Moldova; something that represents 
the main obstacle for a definitive political solution to the 
conflict in the east of Moldova. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16501 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov052_h_94002" </HT>


