<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze: Four UN States To Send Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603175494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1603 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: by Nikolay </F>
Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir Shishlin] 
  [Text] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze stated that four 
UN member-states had agreed to send their troops to Abkhazia on 
a UN peacekeeping mission. He did not tell the Georgian 
parliament which particular countries were meant, but noted that 
their number might increase. 
  He told Interfax that the Georgian parliament's decision to 
dismiss the Abkhazian parliament was somewhat hasty and not 
quite justified from the tactical point of view. "However, in 
principle, it does not contradict the political context of the 
situation," he said. IF Note: The Georgian parliament ruled 
that pending parliamentary elections in Abkhazia the functions 
of the Abkhazian parliament will be performed by the Abkhazian 
Council of Ministers which will be granted the status of a 
temporarily evacuated body. The resolution also says that all 
the laws, adopted by the Abkhazian separatists, shall be 
considered invalid. 
  Chairman of the Abkhazian parliament Vladislav Ardzinba told 
Interfax that the talks on settling the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict would not be continued until the Georgian parliament 
annulled its resolution. He also said that the peace-making 
process was interrupted through Georgia's fault. 
  On Tuesday, the Abkhazian parliament circulated a statement 
which says that no further talks would be held on peaceful 
settlement of the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict. 
  The Georgian parliament's decision to dismiss the Abkhazian 
parliament and to put the Abkhazian deputies on trial 
"illustrates that Georgia has put the stake on military solution 
again," says this document. 
  The Abkhazian parliament qualified the Georgian parliment's 
revolution as illegal, because Abkhazia, it said, is an 
independent state, not part of Georgia. 
  The statement also says that if the Georgian parliament 
reviewed its decision, the parliament of Abkhazia would continue 
the search for a peaceful settlement of the conflict. 
  Russia's Foreign Ministry expressed concern about this 
situation and about a real threat of armed clashes. 
  To quote Grigoriy Karasin, the head of the Russian Foreign 
Ministry's Department for Information and the Press, 
"Georgian-Abkhazian relations have deteriorated, producing a 
real threat of an armed conflict." At the final stage of the 
talks in New York, Georgia openly threatened to step back onto 
the path of war if Abkhazia did not unconditionally recognize 
Georgia's territorial integrity and agree to accept all Georgian 
refugees," he said. 
  He announced that Russia was making urgent steps to prevent 
armed clashes in Abkhazia and interruption of the talks. "It 
will also support UN or UN-apporved peacekeeping operations in 
Abkhazia, based, if necessary, on a Russian military 
contingent," said Karasin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

