<H3> <TI>   New Opposition Movement Formed in Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603180294 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1605 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A group of prominent public and political leaders 
announced the creation of a new movement in Moscow today. It is 
called Accord for the Sake of Russia [Soglsiye vo imiya Rossii]. 
  Its main tasks are to avert the final disintegration of the 
country, to halt the destruction of production capabilities, to 
protect the market and the national capital, and to prevent 
unemployment and hunger, allowing every citizen of the country 
to live at a proper subsistence level and in a dignified way. 
  Dmitriy Pinsker, our parliamentary correspondent, has asked 
the authors of today's appeal to the citizens of Russia to 
explain what the new movement is about. 
  [Begin Pinsker recording] The future belongs to this 
movement 
-- it is a force which consolidates all patriotic parties and 
associations, Anatoliy Lukyanov told a correspondent from Ekho 
Moskvy. He stressed that he had taken part in the drafting of 
the appeal, but does not see any necessity as yet to sign it. 
Mikhail Lapshin, the leader of the Agrarian Party, thinks that 
the creation of the Accord for the Sake of Russia is not a step 
towards confrontation with the president but, on the contrary, a 
desire to achieve civic accord. 
  It should be noted that Vasiliy Lipitskiy, whose name is 
given as one of the founders, told an Ekho Moskvy correspondent 
that it was the first time he heard of this movement, never mind 
his participation in it. [end recording] 
  Let me add that today's appeal to the citizens of Russia has 
been signed by Valeriy Zorkin, Gennadiy Zyuganov, Sergey 
Baburin, Aleksandr Prokhanov, Aleksandr Tsypko, Nikita 
Mikhalkov, and a number of others. 

</TEXT>

