<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Staff `Ready To Shut Down' Nuclear Power Station </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1603160594 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1700 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM1603160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By V. Simonenko; from the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Staff at Kursk nuclear power station are threatening 
to go on hunger strike, boycott the oblast Duma elections, and 
cut off the current to the power lines and so cause problems in 
the unified power grid unless debts are paid off. The nuclear 
power industry workers are demanding that around 86 billion 
rubles owed for electricity already supplied and three-month 
wage arrears are paid. These demands have been sent to the 
Russian Government by a joint decision of the station's 
management board and labor collective councils. The deadline 
set for meeting these demands is 10 March. But even right now 
the total capacity of the station's four power units is down by 
50 percent. Nuclear fuel reserves at the Kursk nuclear power 
station are running out. Suppliers are unwilling to deliver 
without payment. For the time being Kursk power station workers 
are working without pay. The station's safe and reliable 
operation is nonetheless guaranteed. Nuclear energy, even when 
used for peaceful purposes, must not be tinkered with. But 
staff are ready to shut down the station. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16532 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov052_d_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-052 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

