<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kostroma Election Results Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1603154594 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 16 Mar 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM1603154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Yuriy Vakhrin: "They Have Elected </F>
Duma Deputies and Ruined Referendum"] 
  [Text] Kostroma -- All 15 deputies' seats in the Kostroma 
Oblast Duma have been filled as a result of the elections held 
last Sunday. The present "generals" of executive power -- two 
deputy governors, three heads of rural rayon administrations, 
and other officials -- have gotten through in single formation. 
  The level of Kostroma voters' activeness was as a whole 
relatively high: According to preliminary figures at least 38 
percent of voters took part in voting. It is true that the city 
inhabitants demonstrated no particular eagerness to make use of 
their legal right. That is why there was no referendum in 
Kostroma to approve the statute on local self-management. 
Incidentally, this statute, submitted by the mayor of Kostroma, 
Federation Council Deputy Boris korobov, markedly expanded the 
rights of the representative municipal organ compared with what 
was determined by the Russian president's edicts. 
  To determine the fate of this document, at least half of the 
voters should have gone to the polling stations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

