<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Approves Law on Peacekeeping Personnel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603195794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1748 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 16 TASS -- The lower house of the 
Russian parliament approved in the first reading a federal draft 
law "On the order of involving military and civil personnel of 
the Russian Federation in operations for the maintenance or 
restoration of international peace and security and other kinds 
of peace-keeping activities." 
  Russian deputy defence minister, Georgiy Kondratyev, 
addressed lawmakers today, saying that over 16,000 Russian 
servicemen are performing their duties in hot beds of tension on 
our planet in the framework of a peace-keeping mission. 
  Lawmakers took into account appeals made by Russian Defence 
Ministry officials who pointed out that the law was a matter of 
vital importance. It was pointed out that Russia's 
participation in peace-keeping activities, connected with 
continuing instability in areas adjoining Russia's territory, 
and Russia's membership in the U.N. make it necessary to create 
a corresponding legal basis which does not exist at present. 
  The law, adopted in the first reading, determines the order, 
rights and duties of bodies of state power when resolving 
matters of sending military or civil contingents on 
peace-keeping missions outside the Russian federation. 

</TEXT>

