<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin Said `Most Influential Figure' in Duma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603192694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1638 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] State Duma Speaker Ivan Rybkin was the most 
influential figure in the Russian parliament's lower chamber. 
His rating was 7.1 on a ten-point scale (slightly down from 8.0 
points last January), experts of the Russian Federation's 
Political Research Center announced. 
  Communist leader Gennadiy Zyuganov ranks second -- 6.1 
points 
compared to 5.7 points in January. 
  Third comes Vladimir Isakov, leader of the Agrarian Party -- 
5.8 points compared to 3.7 in January. 
  Political scientists believe that the communists' and 
agrarians' strong position is due to the success of the 
political amnesty granted to the 1991 coup leaders and the 
organizers of the hardline revolt last October, initiated by 
them. 
  Leader of the Liberal Democratic Party Vladimir Zhirinovskiy 
ranks fourth -- 5.5 points compared to 6.9 last January. 
Russia's Choice leader Yegor Gaydar went down from second place 
in January (6.4 points) to fifth -- 4.9 points. 
  Observers also point to a noticeable success of former 
minister of foreign economic relations Sergey Glazyev, who 
represents the Democratic Party of Russia. He ranked sixth in 
February, scoring 4.8 points (compared to 3.2 points in 
January). Experts explain his success by the fact that Glazyev 
had advanced his own economic program. 

</TEXT>

