<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Holds News Conference in Moscow 16 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603191894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1809 
GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 16 Mar -- The agreement signed by the 
defense ministers of Armenia and Azerbaijan and the 
Nagorno-Karabakh military representative with the mediation of 
the Russian defense minister in Moscow on 18 February does not 
infringe the rights and dignity of any state and should be 
observed. This was stated by Army General Pavel Grachev, chief 
of the Russian military department, at a meeting with 
journalists. He is not satisfied with how the agreement is 
being observed as "none of the sides is totally fulfilling the 
obligations undertaken." "Unfortunately, percentage-wise the 
Azerbaijani side is the one least fulfilling the agreement," 
Pavel Grachev noted. 
  The leadership of Azerbaijan, in the minister's words, is 
categorically against bringing troops into the conflict region, 
which would make it possible to withdraw the troops of both 
sides some 20-30 km from where they are deployed. Grachev 
called this circumstance "a stumbling block." 
  The Russian defense minister informed journalists that on 15 
March he refused to meet the heads of the military departments 
of Armenia and Azerbaijan, who arrived in Moscow, and stated 
that he does not intend to meet them until they comply with the 
agreement which had been signed with his participation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

