<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Control of Strategic Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603194894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1817 
GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Kondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 16 March -- Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev intends on 17 and 18 March to visit military formations 
and units in Kaliningrad oblast. He announced this today at a 
meeting with journalists. 
  The head of the country's defense department denied reports 
by some of the foreign mass media that he had not left for 
Leningrad military district because of extreme social tension in 
society requiring, it is claimed, the presence in Moscow of a 
"strong hand." He also said that the reports that troops in 
Moscow military district had allegedly been put on an enhanced 
readiness footing were false. 
  At the ITAR-TASS correspondent's request Pavel Grachev 
explained that he is one of those in possession of a so-called 
nuclear button. One button is with the Russian President, who is 
at present in Sochi; the second button is with himself; and the 
third is with the Chief of the General Staff, who has gone to 
France on a working visit. Pavel Grachev emphasized that, 
although the president has in his possession a control system 
for the strategic nuclear forces in the form of a "small nuclear 
case," there should always be one of the military leaders in 
Moscow at the permanent control point. 
  "This evening, the Chief of the General Staff is returning 
from Paris, and tomorrow I shall be leaving for Kaliningrad in 
accordance with the plan for visiting troops", Pavel Grachev 
stated in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

