<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Order to Retarget Missiles </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603153294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1459 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov; Moscow </F>
ITAR-TASS in English at 1544 GMT on 16 March transmits a service 
message killing this item] 
  [Text] Moscow, 16 Mar 16 TASS -- Shifting of targets of 
Russia's nuclear missiles does no damage to security of the 
Russian Federation and other states but is a manifestation of 
confidence and strengthening of strategic stability, Russian 
Defense Minister Pavel Grachev told ITAR-TASS here today. 
  The defense minister was commenting on Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin's recent order assigning the Defense Ministry 
before May 30 "to take measures aimed at organizing the everyday 
activities of the strategic nuclear forces with non-targeted 
missiles". 
  Pavel Grachev added that the issue on the mutual 
non-targeting of strategic weapons of Russia and the United 
States was raised for the first time at a meeting of the two 
presidents in Vancouver last year. In January this year Boris 
Yeltsin and Bill Clinton confirmed in the Moscow Declaration 
that they would give the appropriate instructions to their 
defense ministries. 
  According to the Russian defense minister, Britain also 
joined this initiative. 
  Pavel Grachev believes that terms of implementing this 
decision will be determined by organizational and technical 
possibilities, and are specific for each kind of strategic 
weapons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

