<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Army Funding </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603155594 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1200 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Grachev remarks are recorded; from the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Russia's Defense Minister Pavel Grachev held a news 
conference in Moscow today at which he spoke of the problems of 
organizational development in the Russian Army. According to 
him, the Army today cannot be provided with new military 
equipment as needed because defense enterprises are in a 
catastrophic state, i.e, in a state of forced conversion. The 
Ministry of Defense owes them a huge sum of money. 
  However, Pavel Grachev stated publicly for the first time 
that the Army is being financed at such a low level that there 
would be a complete breakdown if it is any lower. 
  [Grachev] That is what the budget which, unfortunately, the 
Ministry of Finance is offering us, could lead to; the Ministry 
of Finance, which, you see, knows all about how to maintain the 
army and on what budget. 
  As to the problem of the Black Sea Fleet, Pavel Grachev 
believes it should be settled in accordance with the Massandra 
Agreement between Ukraine and Russia, according to which the 
Ukrainian part of the fleet, after an appropriate inventory, 
would be passed over to Russia. 
  [Grachev] Russia will pay suitably for leasing this part of 
the fleet, and the fleet stays unified and indivisible, as at 
present. But this is being done with a lot of difficulties. 
  Pavel Grachev read the journalists a message from Admiral 
Baltin which reports continuing acts of the Ukrainian powers 
that use special purpose troops and OMON [Special Purpose 
Militia Detachment] forces with the aim of forcing the personnel 
of the fleet to take the oath of allegiance to Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

