<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Leaves for Working Visit to Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603120394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1155 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Almaty March 16 TASS -- Kazakhstan's state 
delegation headed by Prime Minister Sergey Tereshchenko set off 
on Wednesday for a working visit to Moscow. The visit aims to 
pave the way for the proposed Kazakh-Russian summit. Under an 
earlier agreeement, the delegation is scheduled to meet for 
talks with Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and 
cabinet members to discuss a wide range of issues of mutual 
concern. 
  These issues can be grouped into four sets, which are of 
especial importance to further development of bilateral 
relations, a spokesman for the Kazakh prime minister reported. 
The two sides will consider military and military-technical 
cooperation, operation of the Baykonur space launching site, 
peaceful use of atomic energy, improvement of ties in the 
economic, scientific, cultural and law spheres. The same 
problems are to be discussed by Presidents Boris Yeltsin of 
Russia and Nursultan Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan during their 
summit scheduled for late March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

