<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Negotiator Views Resumption of Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1603201394 Tallinn ETA in English 1723 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1603201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["News Release"] </F>
  [Text] Tallinn, March 16 -- Inter-state negotiations 
between Estonia and Russia have not been broken off at all, head 
of the Russian delegation Ambassador Vasiliy Svirin told ETA, on 
Wednesday [16 March], adding that it was "strange to hear that 
they were broken and now will resume." 
  During the last round of negotiations on March 1-2 at 
Lohusalu resort near Tallinn, Russia withdraw its earlier 
commitment to pull out its forces by August 31, 1994 and 
neglected to offer another date for negotiations. Yesterday the 
Foreign Ministry of Estonia announced that Estonia had accepted 
Russia's offer to resume negotiations despite "numerous and 
often vague statements from the Russian part on breaking off the 
negotiations". 
  Svirin said that at the last round of negotiations "new, 
unexpected moments came up" and the Russian side had to think 
the situation over" to work out their position. [quotation marks 
as received] 
  The next round will be held in Moscow on April 5-6. 
  Commenting on the possible Estonian-Russian summit, Svirin 
said that it was extremely important, but declined to enlarge on 
the topic, saying only that it had to be prepared very 
thoroughly in order it to be "epochal" in the difficult 
relations between Estonia and Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

