<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   May Have Been Shot Down </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803132694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1304 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 18 TASS -- Russian military experts do 
not rule out a possiblity that the Iranian C-130 plane which 
crashed near Stepanakert in Nagorno-Karabakh late on Thursday 
[17 March] had been shot down by a mobile antiaircraft missile. 
  The depressurised plane was flying at a low altitude and 
might have been mistaken for an alien craft by the warring sides 
in the enclave, the experts told ITAR-TASS on Friday. 
  They added that there are enough weapons in the combat zone, 
including the "Stinger" missiles, capable of destroying 
low-altitude targets. 
  Experts said their fears are also based on the fact that 
contact with the plane was lost all of a sudden and parts of the 
craft discovered on the ground show that the explosion had 
occurred in the air. 
  Such character of damages "happens after a strike of an 
anti- 
aircraft missile," experts said. 
  They also said it is necessary to find out why the plane had 
deviated from the pre-set route. 
  The experts categorically denied a possibility that the 
plane 
was going to land in stepanakert as the runway there is too 
short for such a class of aircraft. The crew undoubtedly knew 
about that, they added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16566 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov053bb_94003" </HT>


