<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crash Caused by `Depressurization' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803135394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1329 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Bocharov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 18 TASS -- The reason for the crash of 
an Iranian C-130 military aircraft whose debris were found this 
morning near Stepanakert, Nagorno-Karabakh, is cockpit 
depressurization, well-informed sources told ITAR-TASS today. 
  Judging by radio talks of the crew and the air traffic 
controllers, a possibility of the plane's shot down in the 
Karabakh skies is minimum. 
  The C-130 plane, an analogue of the U.S. Hercules or the 
Russian AN-12, belongs to the Iranian Defence Ministry. It came 
to Moscow's Sheremetyevo airport several days ago to bring 52 
Iranian servicemen studying in Moscow. On Wednesday [16 March] 
the plane was expected to leave for Tehran, but the take off was 
delayed till Thursday night. 
  The plane finally took off at 18:40 on March 17 carrying 32 
passengers, including 19 family members of staffers of the 
Iranian Embassy in Moscow, and 13 crew members, and headed for 
Tehran. 
  However, flying at a height of 6,300 meters at 19:54 the 
crew 
commander got in touch with the Petrovskoye separate homing 
radio station and said the plane's cockpit had turned 
depressurized and they are losing height. Some time later he 
reported that their height is 5,100 meters. 
  The crew commander had an impression that the situation 
improved and climbed the height of 6,300 meters again. At that 
time an Aeroflot plane was flying in the opposite direction on 
its way from Iran. 
  The Iranian plane commander informed the Russian colleague 
he 
had a permission to cross the Russian and Armenian state 
borders. The conversation registered in the area of the Dzhulfe 
populated locality was the last. After that the Iranian 
military plane lost contact with the air traffic controllers and 
the flying aircraft. 
  Smoking debris of the Iranian plane and 32 dead bodies were 
found early this morning four kilometers away from Stepanakert. 
  The Iranian side has requested assistance in the air crash 
investigation from the Sheremetyevo international services and 
asked local bodies not to touch the debris. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16567 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov053bb_94004" </HT>


