<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Opposition, Majority Differ on New Constitution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1703130094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 17 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK1703130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vitaliy Tsygankov: "First Constitution of </F>
Independent State Passed. Opposition and Majority Differ on 
Republic's Fundamental Law"] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Zenon Poznyak, leader of the 
parliamentary opposition Belarus National Front, commenting in 
an exclusive interview to your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent 
on the adoption of the Constitution, stated: "This Constitution 
has been passed only to introduce a presidential system designed 
for one specific person, Prime Minister Vyacheslav Kebich; and 
for one political action, presidential elections. Other than 
this, the Constitution is not going to work in a normal way; 
neither will the presidential system of government, because it 
does not provide for balanced relations between local 
authorities and the Supreme Soviet, between the president and 
the Supreme Soviet, between the executive and judicial powers. 
The Constitution has been designed to suit a totalitarian 
regime and the specific figure of Kebich, who actually has the 
Supreme Soviet in his hands now. It is designed to give Kebich 
absolute power in a legitimate way. Should another president 
come along, he would not be able to do anything in this 
unbalanced system, and would be drawn into conflict with the 
Supreme Soviet and local authorities. 
  Members of the parliamentary majority naturally see the 
adoption of the Constitution quite differently. Nikolay 
Skorigin, adviser to the prime minister and coordinator of the 
most influential "Belarus" parliamentary group, referred in an 
interview for your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent to the 
above accusations: "This is simply ridiculous. How could the 
Constitution have been designed over two and a half years for 
one person? All the more so because no one can be dead sure of 
who is going to be elected first president of the Republic of 
Belarus." 
  "From the legal point of view, the passing of the 
Constitution is a foundation for the state's entire legal base, 
and from the political point of view, it is a legal guarantee of 
ensuring stability in the state. We have managed to cross the 
Rubicon from the old Constitution, which was a brake on creating 
a rule-of-law state, to the new Constitution without a single 
drop of blood having been shed. This is a great victory for 
what seems to be a virtually inefficient parliament." This is 
the opinion of Dmitriy Bulakhov, chairman of the parliamentary 
commission on legislation. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16574 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov053_g_94002" </HT>


