<H3> <TI>   Deputy Premier Announces Karbovanets To Be Devalued </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703152794 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1225 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Ukraine has announced its intention of devaluing the 
karbovanets in the near future without introducing a floating 
exchange rate based on market dealings. Valentyn Landyk, the 
Republic's deputy prime minister told INTERFAX that the Cabinet 
of Ministers held a special conference devoted to the formation 
of a currency rate policy. The conference did not produce a 
final agreement on a mechanism for currency regulation. 
However, it is expected that a decision on this will be taken 
in the next few days. 
  The exchange rate for cash karbovantsy at exchange points at 
present is about 40,000 to the dollar. The official rate is 
used by the state to purchase half of the foreign currency 
incomes of exporters and other payments. At the end of 1993, 
inflation in Ukraine was over 60 percent per month but in 
January it fell below 20 percent. 

</TEXT>

