<H3> <TI>   Final Results of Parliamentary Elections Issued </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703115194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1000 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Almaty, 17 March TASS -- Kazakhstan has summed up 
final results of its parliamentary elections held on March [as 
received]. 
  The central electoral commission has announced that 73.52 
[as 
received] of all eligible voters took part in the polls, 
electing 176 people (154 men and 22 women) to sit in the 
parliament. 
  As concerns ethnic backgrounds, the new parliamentarians 
consist of 105 Kazakhs, 49 Russians, 10 Ukrainians, three 
Germans, three Jews, one Uzbek, one Tatar, one Korean, one Pole, 
and one Uigur. 
  Forty-two people were elected from the state list, 75 were 
nominated by public associations and 59 were self-nominated. 
  According to independent analysts, at least 60 per cent of 
the newly-elected parliamentarians are reliable supporters of 
Nursultan Nazarbayev, and they will therefore be able to control 
the majority in line with Nazarbyaev's wishes. 

</TEXT>

