<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Praises Partnership for Peace Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703151294 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1030 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1703151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau BASAPRESS, 17/3/1994 -- President Mircea 
Snegur took the floor during the signing ceremony of the 
"Partnership For Peace" Document, in Brussels on 16 March. He 
noted that being in a very important geo-strategic zone at the 
intersection of numerous interests, by the help of the program 
the Republic of Moldova will strive for consolidation of peace 
and good will and for the solution of the various and 
complicated problems it presently faces, based on international 
principles and rights. "We are also ready to elaborate as soon 
as possible the document of attendance for the signing of the 
bilateral agreement of partnership that will define the 
character and degree of Moldova's cooperation with corresponding 
NATO structures," said Snegur. He declared that Moldova is 
interested in an effective participation in the program, "with 
the certainty that it will offer us favorable opportunities for 
the creation of a professional army, in accordance with 
requirements, democratic principles and international 
standards." Mircea Snegur stressed that the Republic of Moldova 
pays special attention to the consultations on security 
stipulated by the program, especially in the case when a member 
state deems its territorial integrity, political independence or 
national security threatened. According to President Snegur, 
"today these principles are violated by the presence of foreign 
troops on Moldovan territory. This fact is in our opinion the 
biggest obstacle for the final political solution of the 
conflict in Moldova's Eastern regions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

