<H3> <TI>   Entry `Being Studied' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703181794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1652 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" Feature compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov and Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Kyrgyzstan will evidently refrain from joining 
NATO's Partnership for Peace program, said the chief of the 
international department of the president's office, Bakit 
Abdrisayev, in an interview with INTERFAX. 
  According to Askar Akayev's expert on world politics, the 
possibility of his country's joining the program is being 
studied, and "the approach to it is very cautious," since 
Bishkek is bound by its commitments in the framework of 
collective security treaties signed with CIS countries. 
  As INTERFAX learned from the chief of the Kyrgyz Defence 
Ministry's press center, Lt.-Colonel Akzhal Isayev, his ministry 
has not determined its attitude to the NATO program yet, since 
the military are not acquainted with it. 

</TEXT>

